detail_description: When exploring Zaragoza, a must-visit is the Mercado Central de Zaragoza, a vibrant marketplace that has been at the heart of the city since its opening in 1903. This stunning structure showcases beautiful iron and glass architecture typical of the 19th century, creating an inviting atmosphere for visitors. Inside, you'll be greeted by a sensory feast—an array of fresh produce bursting with color, along with regional delicacies like meats, cheeses, and fish.
name: Mercado Central de Zaragoza
address: Av. de César Augusto, 110, Casco Antiguo, 50003 Zaragoza, Spain

excerpt: UNESCO-listed 11th-century palace now used as seat of the Aragonese Parliament, with guided tours.
detail_description: Aljafería Palace, also known as Palacio de la Aljaferia, is a must-visit in Zaragoza. This 11th-century palace serves as the seat of the Aragonese Parliament and offers guided tours. The palace's fortified exterior contrasts with its stunning interior featuring Mudejar art declared a UNESCO World Heritage site. Inside, visitors can admire the breathtaking myrhab, alveolate arches, an orange tree patio, and the golden hall.
name: Aljafería Palace
address: C. de los Diputados, s/n, 50004 Zaragoza, Spain

excerpt: Renaissance mansion housing paintings & prints by Francisco de Goya, plus other Spanish artists.
detail_description: The Goya Museum, located in a Renaissance mansion, showcases an impressive collection of paintings and prints by Francisco de Goya along with works by other Spanish artists. The museum's exhibition is centered around the Aragonese painter's work, featuring 14 paintings, a drawing, and the complete series of Goya's engravings. Visitors can also explore author-themed museums such as the Pablo Gargallo Museum and the IAACC Pablo Serrano to experience different artistic styles.
name: Goya Museum
address: C. de Espoz y Mina, 23, Casco Antiguo, 50003 Zaragoza, Spain

excerpt: 1908 museum dedicated to archaeology & fine art, with Roman & Islamic artefacts & paintings by Goya.
detail_description: The Zaragoza Museum, established in 1908, is a treasure trove of archaeology and fine art. It houses an impressive collection of Roman and Islamic artifacts as well as captivating paintings by the renowned artist Goya. The museum offers a rich cultural experience with its diverse exhibition rooms and monuments. One can explore archaeological items from the province of Zaragoza and a significant Goya collection among other pieces.
name: Zaragoza Museum
address: Pl. de los Sitios, 6, Casco Antiguo, 50001 Zaragoza, Spain

excerpt: Large city park with botanical gardens, sculptures & fountains plus cafes & bicycle rentals.
detail_description: Parque Grande José Antonio Labordeta is a sprawling city park in Zaragoza, offering a serene escape from urban life. It features botanical gardens, sculptures, and fountains, as well as amenities like cafes and bicycle rentals. The park spans over 40 hectares and boasts around 15 fountains, a botanic garden, viewpoints, terraces, paths, statues, and even a swimming pool for the summer months.
name: Parque Grande José Antonio Labordeta
address: Parque Grande de José Antonio Labordeta, s/n, 50006 Zaragoza, Spain

excerpt: Original artworks from 20th century Spanish sculptor Pablo Gargallo in a Renaissance-style palace.
detail_description: The Pablo Gargallo Museum, located in the historic Old Town district of Zaragoza, is dedicated to showcasing the remarkable sculptures of 20th-century Spanish artist Pablo Gargallo. Housed in the Renaissance-style Argillo Palace, this museum offers a glimpse into the mastery of Gargallo's avant-garde art. Visitors can also explore temporary exhibitions and year-round events at this cultural venue.
name: Pablo Gargallo Museum
address: Pl. de S. Felipe, 3, Casco Antiguo, 50003 Zaragoza, Spain

excerpt: Zaragoza is the capital of northeastern Spain's Aragon region. Overlooking the Ebro River in the city center is baroque Nuestra Señora del Pilar basilica, a famous pilgrimage site with a shrine to the Virgin Mary and multiple domes. Mudéjar-style landmarks, combining Islamic and Gothic architecture, include the Aljafería, an 11th-century Moorish palace, and the Cathedral of the Savior, begun in the 12th century.
detail_description: Zaragoza, the capital of Spain's Aragon region, is a charming city with a mix of architectural styles. The Nuestra Señora del Pilar basilica, overlooking the Ebro River, is a famous pilgrimage site with stunning baroque design. The city also boasts Mudéjar-style landmarks like the Aljafería palace and the Cathedral of the Savior. Despite its beauty, some visitors have noted an unpleasant smell in certain areas.
name: Zaragoza
address: Spain

detail_description: Sala de Exposiciones La Lonja, located in Zaragoza, Spain, is a stunning example of Renaissance architecture influenced by Florentine and Mudejar styles. Built between 1541 and 1551 as the city's commercial exchange center, it has since become the most important exhibition space in Zaragoza. This historical landmark showcases the best art exhibitions from around the world and is considered one of the finest examples of Aragonese-Renaissance design.
name: Sala de Exposiciones La Lonja
address: Pl. de Ntra. Sra. del Pilar, s/n, Casco Antiguo, 50003 Zaragoza, Spain

excerpt: Elaborate courtyard from a 1550s merchant's house with friezes, columns, arches & balconies.
detail_description: Fundación Ibercaja Patio de la Infanta is a captivating 16th-century Renaissance courtyard nestled in the heart of Zaragoza. Originally part of a merchant's house, it was later transformed into a private residence for the Aragonese Infanta Catherine of Austria. The courtyard boasts stunning architectural features such as friezes, columns, arches, and balconies that showcase the city's rich history.
name: Fundación Ibercaja Patio de la Infanta
address: C. de San Ignacio de Loyola, 16, 50008 Zaragoza, Spain

excerpt: Multimedia museum around archaeological remains of a Roman forum from the time of Emperor Augustus.
detail_description: The Museo del Foro de Caesaraugusta, located in Zaragoza, Spain, is a captivating museum dedicated to the ancient Roman forum of Caesaraugusta. This multimedia museum offers visitors a chance to explore the archaeological remains of the forum, which was once the political, social, and economic center of the Roman city. As you wander through the museum, you can walk along recreated streets of the forum and see depictions of shops and vendors from that era.
name: Museo del Foro de Caesaraugusta
address: Pl. de la Seo, 2, Casco Antiguo, 50001 Zaragoza, Spain

name: Monumento "la Cruz de Piedra del Puente de Piedra" en Zaragoza
address: Puente de Piedra, Casco Antiguo, 50014 Zaragoza, Spain

excerpt: Stately 15th-century stone bridge spanning the Ebro River, known for imposing stone lion statues.
detail_description: The Stone Bridge Zaragoza, also known as Puente de Piedra, is a historic 15th-century bridge that spans the Ebro River and serves as an iconic landmark in the city. Adorned with imposing stone lion statues, this picturesque bridge offers stunning views of Zaragoza and the river, making it a popular destination for both locals and tourists. Visitors can take leisurely strolls across the bridge, capturing photographs of the scenic surroundings.
name: Stone Bridge
address: Puente de Piedra, Casco Antiguo, 50001 Zaragoza, Spain

excerpt: Aquarium with a wide range of fish & other animals found in rivers throughout the world.
detail_description: The Aquarium River of Zaragoza, originally part of the Expo 2008 venue, now offers a green space with wild nature just minutes from the city center. Visitors can enjoy modern buildings from the exhibition alongside the natural meander of the Ebro. The aquarium is known as Europe's largest river aquarium and houses 4,000 animals from major rivers worldwide.
name: Aquarium River of Zaragoza
address: Av. de José Atarés, s/n, 50018 Zaragoza, Spain

excerpt: Contemporary works by local & international painters & sculptors in an eye-catching building.
detail_description: IAACC Pablo Serrano, also known as the Aragonese Institute of Contemporary Art and Culture, is a striking building that houses an impressive collection of modern art. Located in Zaragoza, it serves as a hub for contemporary culture, offering not only visual arts but also dance, music, and literature.
name: IAACC Pablo Serrano
address: P.º de María Agustín, 20, Casco Antiguo, 50004 Zaragoza, Spain

detail_description: Plaza de Nuestra Senora del Pilar, also known as Mercardo de Lanuza or Mercado Central, is a bustling market located next to the Roman Walls in Saragossa. It is particularly lively in the mornings on weekdays, offering visitors and locals the opportunity to experience a real working market atmosphere while purchasing fresh and healthy food. This expansive plaza is one of the largest in Europe, stretching alongside the cathedral and various other buildings.
name: Plaza de Nuestra Senora del Pilar
address: Casco Antiguo, 50003 Zaragoza, Spain

detail_description: La Lonja, located in Plaza de la Pilar, is a remarkable Renaissance building that once served as a Merchants Exchange or market. Today, it functions as an exhibition hall. The building was constructed by the council between 1541-1551 to provide an alternative location for commercial activities, away from the church. Visitors can enjoy fresh and competitively priced fish at this venue.
name: La Lonja
address: P.º de Longares, 13, 50014 Zaragoza, Spain

excerpt: Archeological remains of a 1st-century AD Roman arena at the city's highest point, revealed in 1972.
detail_description: The Museo del Teatro de Caesaraugusta in Zaragoza offers a captivating journey into the city's Roman history. It features the archaeological remains of a 1st-century AD Roman arena, uncovered in 1972. The museum showcases the ancient Roman theater, once accommodating 6,000 spectators. Visitors can enjoy panoramic views of the excavation process from the ground floor and explore audiovisual presentations and 3D models depicting its former grandeur in the basement.
name: Museo del Teatro de Caesaraugusta
address: C. de San Jorge, 12, Casco Antiguo, 50001 Zaragoza, Spain

excerpt: Ornate Catholic church, rebuilt in the 19th century, with sarcophagi dating from the 1st century.
detail_description: The Basílica of Santa Engracia Church is a stunning example of ornate Catholic architecture, originally constructed in 1511 and completed by 1517. This remarkable structure underwent renovations in the 18th century, showcasing an impressive facade adorned with intricate medallions and sculptures representing various saints. Inside, visitors can explore its captivating crypt housing ancient sarcophagi from the 1st century, which are remnants of early Christian artistry.
name: Basílica of Santa Engracia Church
address: C. de Tomás Castellano, 1, Casco Antiguo, 50001 Zaragoza, Spain

excerpt: Craft fairs & flea markets in a busy square with a 1908 sculpture of key figures from city history.
detail_description: Plaza de los Sitios in Zaragoza is a bustling square featuring craft fairs and flea markets, as well as a 1908 sculpture of key historical figures. The square is home to the Museo de Zaragoza, housed in a neo-Renaissance building constructed for the Hispano-French Exposition. It also boasts a picturesque inner city park with a delightful fountain and two children's play areas.
name: Plaza de los Sitios de Zaragoza
address: Pl. de los Sitios, 5, Casco Antiguo, 50001 Zaragoza, Spain

excerpt: Colorful cupolas top this Baroque edifice with a famed shrine to the Virgin Mary & frescoes by Goya.
detail_description: The Cathedral-Basilica of Our Lady of the Pillar is a stunning Baroque structure adorned with vibrant cupolas and renowned for its shrine to the Virgin Mary. Inside, visitors can admire frescoes by Goya. While it's worth exploring this architectural gem, nearby villages like Aninon and Torralba de Ribota boast exceptional examples of Mudejar architecture, such as the Church of Lady of Castillo and the Church of San Felix.
name: Cathedral-Basilica of Our Lady of the Pillar
address: Plaza del Pilar, s/n, Casco Antiguo, 50003 Zaragoza, Spain

excerpt: Art shows, screenings & talks in a geometric concrete & aluminium structure designed by Carme Pinós.
detail_description: Located in Zaragoza, CaixaForum Zaragoza is a modern cultural center housed in a striking geometric concrete and aluminum structure designed by Carme Pinós. The venue offers a diverse range of exhibitions, screenings, and talks suitable for all ages. Visitors can immerse themselves in international culture through art, fashion, photography, and film exhibits and workshops. In addition to its cultural offerings, the center's avant-garde building itself is an intriguing modern architectural attraction.
name: CaixaForum Zaragoza
address: Av. de José Anselmo Clavé, 4, Delicias, 50004 Zaragoza, Spain

excerpt: Historic church, founded in the 13th century, with Gothic & Moorish architectural elements.
detail_description: The Parish Church of San Pablo, also known as Iglesia de San Pablo, is a historic church in Zaragoza with a rich heritage dating back to the 13th century. It features a captivating blend of Gothic and Moorish architectural styles. Situated in the traditional San Pablo neighborhood, it holds significant cultural and religious importance as the third most important Catholic Church in Saragossa city.
name: Parish Church of San Pablo
address: C. de San Pablo, 42, Casco Antiguo, 50003 Zaragoza, Spain

detail_description: In the charming city of Zaragoza, one of the must-visit attractions is the Arco del Deán. This beautiful archway, dating back to the 16th century, is located in a neighborhood with a medieval ambiance near the Cathedral La Seo. Originally built in the 13th century to connect the House and the Cathedral, it features Gothic windows and decorative Mudejar motifs added in later centuries.
name: Arco del Deán
address: Cathedral of the Savior, C. del Deán, 5, Casco Antiguo, 50001 Zaragoza, Spain

excerpt: Bordered by historic buildings, this large, bustling square features monuments, statues & events.
detail_description: The Plaza of Our Lady of the Pillar, or Plaza del Pilar, is a vibrant and expansive square that serves as the heart of Zaragoza. Surrounded by stunning historic architecture, this pedestrian-friendly area is not only one of the largest squares in Europe but also a hub for cultural events and gatherings. Known affectionately as the 'living room of the city,' it features two magnificent cathedrals: the Basilica del Pilar and La Seo, both architectural marvels worth exploring.
name: Plaza of Our Lady of the Pillar
address: Pl. de Ntra. Sra. del Pilar, Casco Antiguo, 50003 Zaragoza, Spain

detail_description: The Murallas Romanas de Zaragoza, also known as the Roman Walls of Caesaraugusta, are a significant part of Zaragoza's historical and cultural heritage. These ancient walls once encircled the central area of the city, stretching approximately 2 miles with numerous towers and main gates. Constructed with alabaster and limestone ashlars, some sections were up to 7 meters thick.
name: Murallas Romanas de Zaragoza
address: Plaza César Augusto, 3, Casco Antiguo, 50003 Zaragoza, Spain

name: Pl. de España
address: Casco Antiguo, Zaragoza, Spain

detail_description: The Iglesia Parroquial de la Seo, also known as the Cathedral of El Salvador, is a significant religious site in Zaragoza. It stands as the second cathedral in the city and was constructed between 1681 and 1872. This historical landmark holds great importance to the Catholic church, being linked to the first-ever church dedicated to Mary dating back to 40 AD. The interior features a small chapel dedicated to Saint Michael with a stunning Mudejar wall and roof.
name: Iglesia Parroquial de la Seo
address: Pl. de la Seo, 4, Casco Antiguo, 50001 Zaragoza, Spain

excerpt: Cathedral combining Romanesque, Gothic & baroque architecture, plus a medieval tapestry museum.
detail_description: The Cathedral of the Savior of Zaragoza, also known as La Seo, is a stunning architectural marvel that combines Romanesque, Gothic, and Baroque styles. Situated on Plaza de la Seo, it holds historical significance as it was built on the site of one of the first mosques during Moorish rule in Aragon. Over the centuries, it has undergone various renovations and additions reflecting Mudejar, Gothic, Renaissance, and Baroque influences.
name: Cathedral of the Savior of Zaragoza
address: Pl. de la Seo, 4, Casco Antiguo, 50001 Zaragoza, Spain

excerpt: Museum of the art of origami, with special exhibitions & hands-on workshops for kids & adults.
detail_description: Nestled in the heart of Zaragoza, the Escuela Museo de Origami Zaragoza (EMOZ) is a captivating destination for anyone intrigued by the delicate art of paper folding. Established in 2003 through a collaboration between the Spanish Origami Association and local authorities, this unique museum celebrates origami's rich history and creativity. Visitors can explore an impressive collection that features everything from intricate animal designs to stunning geometric forms and even life-sized installations.
name: Escuela Museo de Origami Zaragoza (EMOZ)
address: Pl. de San Agustín, 2, Casco Antiguo, 50002 Zaragoza, Spain

detail_description: El Balcón del Tubo is a vibrant district located in the heart of Zaragoza's historic center, known for its bustling atmosphere, quality tapas, and lively nightlife. The area is lined with numerous bars and restaurants nestled within narrow streets. Surrounding this district are notable historical landmarks such as the Goya Museum, Caesaraugusta Roman Theatre Museum, Pilar Tower, and Basilica Nuestra Senora del Pilar along the banks of River Ebro.
name: El Balcón del Tubo
address: C. de los Estébanes, 7, Casco Antiguo, 50003 Zaragoza, Spain

excerpt: Pedestrian-only central road lined with stately, 19th-century homes.
detail_description: C. de Alfonso I is a charming pedestrian-only street in the historic center of Zaragoza, lined with elegant 19th-century homes and an array of shops. Walking down this picturesque street offers stunning views of the towering basilica and the ornate balconies that adorn the buildings. Along the way, visitors can explore quaint storefronts, stop at local cafes on Placa Sas, and even visit historic passages like Ciclon.
name: C. de Alfonso I
address: Casco Antiguo, 50003 Zaragoza, Spain

detail_description: Located at Plaza Nuestra Senora del Pilar in Zaragoza, the Fuente de la Hispanidad is a remarkable fountain built in 1991 to commemorate Christopher Columbus's discovery of the Americas. Designed by sculptor Francisco Rallo Lahoz, it features a central figure of Columbus surrounded by sculptures representing indigenous cultures from the Americas. The fountain's unique shape resembles that of Latin America when viewed from above, with water cascading down its facade to represent the northern coast of the continent.
name: Fuente de la Hispanidad
address: Pl. de Ntra. Sra. del Pilar, 1, Casco Antiguo, 50003 Zaragoza, Spain

detail_description: The Alma Mater Museum, situated in the former episcopal palace of Zaragoza, offers a captivating journey through the city's religious history. The museum showcases various eras including Romanesque, Gothic, Mudejar and Renaissance periods. Visitors can explore the Bishops Room and Throne Room adorned with portraits by renowned artists like Goya. Multimedia exhibitions and video mapping projections enhance the experience.
name: Alma Mater Museum
address: Pl. de la Seo, 5, Casco Antiguo, 50001 Zaragoza, Spain

detail_description: When visiting Saragossa, a must-see is Torreon de la Zuda, located in the Old Town near Pilar Square. This historic tower dates back to the 16th century and was once part of a Muslim fortress. Today, it serves as a tourist office and information center where visitors can access assistance and learn more about the city. Climbing to the 5th floor offers a stunning panoramic view of Saragossa.
name: Torreon de la Zuda
address: Torre de la Zuda, Glorieta Pío XII, 1, Casco Antiguo, 50003 Zaragoza, Spain

excerpt: Huge 18th-century bullring with a striking exterior featuring tiers of colonnaded brick archways.
detail_description: Plaza de Toros de la Misericordia is an impressive 18th-century bullring known for its striking exterior featuring tiers of colonnaded brick archways. Also referred to as the coso de la misericordia, it was constructed in the early 1900s and stands out as the only bullring in Spain with a retractable cover, allowing visitors to enjoy events even on rainy days.
name: Plaza de Toros de la Misericordia
address: Calle Vicente Gomez Salvo, C. de Ramón Pignatelli, 120, 50004 Zaragoza, Spain

detail_description: P.º de la Independencia is home to La Mafia, an Italian restaurant in the heart of Zaragoza that offers a unique dining experience inspired by the #PiacereOriginale concept. The restaurant presents a new menu featuring the best of Italian-Mediterranean cuisine, including traditional dishes and exclusive specialties. With ample space for over 200 guests, it's an ideal spot for couples, families, and groups to savor authentic Italian flavors in a welcoming atmosphere.
name: P.º de la Independencia
address: Casco Antiguo, Zaragoza, Spain

excerpt: Elevated tasting menus with a focus on regional produce, in an elegant, 1800s locale.
detail_description: Restaurante Casa Lac is a historic establishment dating back to 1825, making it one of the oldest restaurants in Spain. The restaurant's elegant 1800s setting features details such as wrought iron staircases, wooden coffered ceilings, and parquet floors made from exotic woods.
name: Restaurante Casa Lac
address: C. de los Mártires, 12, Casco Antiguo, 50003 Zaragoza, Spain

excerpt: Exhibition halls displaying a rare collection of Flemish tapestries from the 15th–17th centuries.
detail_description: The Tapestry Museum, located within the Seo de Zaragoza Cathedral in Zaragoza, houses an unparalleled collection of 63 Flemish tapestries from the 15th to 17th centuries. This exceptional display is complemented by a variety of gold and silver works, sacred ornaments, paintings, sculptures, and reliquaries.
name: Tapestry Museum
address: Pl. de la Seo, 4, Casco Antiguo, 50001 Zaragoza, Spain

detail_description: Zaragoza, a city with numerous tourist attractions, is home to the famous La Seo Cathedral, also known as the Cathedral of the Savior. This significant monument was built in the 12th century on the grounds of a former mosque and has undergone various renovations over time, resulting in its unique and diverse architectural style.
name: Cathedral of the Savior
address: Pl. de la Seo, 4, Casco Antiguo, 50001 Zaragoza, Spain

detail_description: CALZADOS EL TUBO is situated in the lively and bustling district of El Tubo, located in the historic center of Zaragoza. This area is renowned for its vibrant tapas scene, with numerous bars and restaurants offering a diverse array of Spanish delicacies. The narrow cobblestone streets are lined with establishments serving quality tapas, making it a popular meeting spot for locals and visitors alike.
name: Calzados El Tubo
address: C. de Cinegio, 10, Casco Antiguo, 50003 Zaragoza, Spain

excerpt: Rustic-chic venue showcasing local fare, small plates, craft cocktails & beer, plus brunch plates.
detail_description: La Clandestina is a rustic-chic venue known for its local fare, small plates, craft cocktails, and beer. It gained fame for winning the Zaragoza Tapas Contest with its "Cruz de Navajas," which incorporates Aragonese products into an original creation. The cafe exudes a vintage spirit and a laid-back atmosphere that attracts a young crowd for afternoon chats or early evening drinks.
name: La Clandestina
address: Calle San Andrés, 9 Esq, C. de San Jorge, 50001 Zaragoza, Spain

detail_description: Originally the mansion of Miguel Donlope, a wealthy lawyer, the Real Maestranza de Caballeria in Zaragoza is now known for housing this organization. The building's facade showcases typical architectural elements of its time, such as a rounded entrance arch and appealing wooden eaves. Inside, notable features include an impressive wooden dome above the stairwell, ornate plaster decorations, and coffered ceilings in the noble rooms.
name: Real Maestranza de Caballería de Zaragoza
address: C. Diego Dormer, 21, Casco Antiguo, 50001 Zaragoza, Spain

detail_description: Rutica 41 offers an amazing food and wine tour in Zaragoza, a city located amidst the Pyrenees mountains, the La Rioja wine region, and lush forests. The tour takes you to two different wineries in two villages, where you can taste great wines and learn about their history from knowledgeable staff. The guide, Jorge, is highly praised for his organization and knowledge of the area.
name: Rutica 41, Food & Wine Tours in Zaragoza
address: Zarola Tienda, C. de S. Miguel, 31, Casco Antiguo, 50001 Zaragoza, Spain

excerpt: Medieval, baroque & Renaissance architecture around a city square with bars & terraced restaurants.
detail_description: Plaza San Felipe, located in the Old Town area, is a charming square featuring a mix of medieval, baroque, and Renaissance architecture. The iconic San Felipe Church and House of the Marquis of Villaverde with its equestrian sculptures are must-see attractions around the square. The Iglesia de San Felipe y Santiago el Menor overlooks the plaza, showcasing a blend of Baroque and Classical elements.
name: San Felipe Square
address: Pl. de S. Felipe, s/n, Casco Antiguo, 50003 Zaragoza, Spain

detail_description: Harinera ZGZ, located in Zaragoza, is a cultural hub housed in a refurbished flour factory. It offers a variety of activities, workshops, and concerts for the local community. The center provides modern spaces for children's learning and small businesses to operate. Visitors can take guided tours to learn about the building's history and current uses. The center hosts both regular and spontaneous events, providing plenty of free activities for visitors to enjoy.
name: Harinera ZGZ
address: Av. de San José, 201, San José, 50007 Zaragoza, Spain

detail_description: Pabellón Puente, also known as the Bridge Pavilion, is a remarkable structure designed by Zaha Hadid for the 2008 International Expo with a focus on Water and Sustainable Development. This architectural gem has an exquisite exterior and houses the Mobility Museum inside. It's considered an icon of Zaragoza and offers a captivating exhibition of futuristic technology, showcasing the history and utopia of mobility.
name: Pabellón Puente
address: P.º de los Puentes, 50018 Zaragoza, Spain

excerpt: Aragon is a landlocked region in northeastern Spain comprising the provinces of Huesca, Zaragoza and Teruel. It's bisected by the Ebro River, with the Pyrenees Mountains in its north. Aragon is known for its ornate, Moorish-influenced Mudéjar architecture, represented in the 1686 Basilica of Nuestra Senora del Pilar in Zaragoza. The regional capital, Zaragoza is a commercial city of wide boulevards and arcades.
detail_description: Aragon, a region in northeastern Spain, is made up of the provinces of Huesca, Zaragoza, and Teruel. The area is characterized by the Ebro River running through it and the Pyrenees Mountains to the north. Aragon boasts stunning Moorish-influenced Mudéjar architecture, exemplified by landmarks like the Basilica of Nuestra Senora del Pilar in Zaragoza.
name: Aragon
address: Spain

detail_description: The Torre de San Francisco de Borja observation deck is a great place to see stunning views of the city and the river. It's not too expensive, so you can enjoy the experience without worrying about the price.
name: Torre de San Francisco de Borja
address: Pl. de Ntra. Sra. del Pilar, Casco Antiguo, 50003 Zaragoza, Spain

excerpt: Amusement park with a twisty rollercoaster, adult & kids' rides, a pool area & self-service buffet.
detail_description: The Zaragoza Amusement Park is a great place for families to spend a day out. There are plenty of rides and attractions for all ages, as well as a pool area with self-service food. The park can get quite crowded, but it's well worth the wait if you're looking for an enjoyable day out.
name: Zaragoza Amusement Park
address: P.º del Duque de Alba, 15, 50007 Zaragoza, Spain

excerpt: Museum inside a church, depicting the elaborate stained-glass creations of the Crystal Rosary.
detail_description: The Museo de los Faroles y Rosario de Cristal is a museum inside a church that showcases elaborately stained glass creations of the Crystal Rosary. The place is popular with tourists for its beautiful rosary and its permanent exhibitions of various artworks.
name: Museum of Lanterns and Crystal Rosaries
address: Pl. de San Pedro Nolasco, s/n, Casco Antiguo, 50001 Zaragoza, Spain
